sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1767002
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: P(Lac)IQ RBS Aiia RBS LuxR ter ter luxpR RBS tetR ter ter
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
We designed and built a kill switch mechanism that is based on the activation of a lethal gene downstream of an inducible promoter that is activated over time.

The presented part represents the first and the second module of our designed genetic circuit. The here presented BioBrick consists of a constitutive promoter (I14032) driving expression of Aiia and LuxR followed by a Lux promoter (R0062) , driving expression of TetR.

By using this part one can control the amount of producing TetR which means that at the beginning the system will produce TetR. After a certain amount of time thatdepends on the initial concentration of AHL , the system will stop producing TetR due to the absence of AHL that interacts with LuxR to form its active conformation. sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0034
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix.

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS. Contact info for this part: Brian Chow

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: tetR
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Coding region for the TetR protein without the Ribosome Binding Site. Modified with an LVA tail for rapid degradation of the protein and faster fall time for the emission. TetR binds to the pTet regulator (BBa_R0040). aTc (anhydrotetracycline) binds to TetR and inhibits its operation.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: June Rhee, Connie Tao, Ty Thomson, Louis Waldman.

BBa_C0040 TetR Protein is based on the TetR sequence from Elowitz's repressilator. It has been modified to include a rapid degradation LVA tail, and includes the BioBrick standard assembly head and tail restriction sites. The RBS has been removed. The stop codon has been changed from TAA to a double stop codon TAATAA.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0012
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcription terminator for the E.coli RNA polymerase.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Derived from the TE terminator of T7 bacteriophage between Genes 1.3 and 1.4 <genbank>V01146</genbank>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Suggested by Sri Kosuri and Drew Endy as a high efficiency terminator. The 5' end cutoff was placed immediately after the TAA stop codon and the 3' end cutoff was placed just prior to the RBS of Gene 1.4 (before AAGGAG).

Use anywhere transcription should be stopped when the gene of interest is upstream of this terminator.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1767001
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: P(Lac)IQ RBS Aiia RBS LuxR term term luxpR
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: We designed and built a kill switch mechanism that is based on the activation of a lethal gene downstream of an inducible promoter that is activated over time. The presented part is the first module of our designed genetic circuit (BBa_K1767003). In order to characterize and understand each module of the genetic circuit we designed two composite parts that allow us to verify the (1) the degradation rate of AHL by AiiA and (2) induction of the pLux promoter by LuxR in presence of AHL with and without co-expression of AiiA. (1) The here presented BioBrick consists of a constitutive promoter driving expression of AiiA and LuxR followed by a Lux promoter which drives expression of a fluorescent reporter (here: yellow fluorescent protein).
